<li id="cite_note-.C3.93_Ceallaigh-61"><b><a href="#cite_ref-.C3.93_Ceallaigh_61-0" title="">^</a></b> Ó Ceallaigh, Daltún, <i><a href="http://homepage.eircom.net/~mheas/id-art.htmprof#" class="external text" title="http://homepage.eircom.net/~mheas/id-art.htmprof#" rel="nofollow">Along The road to Irish unity?</a></i>--Some sources strongly disagree with Mallon: "As one political scientist has put it, the remark about Good Friday being 'Sunningdale for slow learners' is 'as misleading as it is diverting, since the Agreement is a much more subtle and inclusive bargain than was reached at Sunningdale...' Also, a European Studies expert has said: "...there are... significant differences between them [Sunningdale and Belfast], both in terms of content and the circumstances surrounding their negotiation, implementation, and operation." More pertinently, it has been observed: "In one sense, it could be argued that mainstream unionism could only lose in the talks and the question was really how much would be lost."</li>
